    <section class="guide-body">

      <p>
        Financial documentation is where most business sales succeed or fail. A well-prepared
        financial package accelerates diligence, supports the asking price, and prevents the
        renegotiations that erode deal value. An unprepared financial package invites discounts,
        delays, and deal failures.
      </p>
      <p>
        This guide covers every document you need, how to prepare it, and the specific issues
        that most commonly create problems in diligence.
      </p>

      <h2>The Core Document Checklist</h2>

      <h3>1. Business Tax Returns — 3 Years</h3>
      <p>
        The IRS tax return is the primary source of truth in any business sale. Buyers and SBA lenders
        use it because it represents what you told the government your business made — and it is
        extremely difficult to dispute. Required for all business entity types:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>S-Corp: Form 1120-S, plus Schedule K-1s for all shareholders</li>
        <li>Partnership/LLC taxed as partnership: Form 1065, plus Schedule K-1s</li>
        <li>Sole Proprietorship: Schedule C from personal Form 1040</li>
        <li>C-Corp: Form 1120</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        If you have an extension for the most recent tax year, provide a signed copy of the
        extension and the most recent quarterly estimated tax filings, along with an explanation
        of the timeline. Buyers understand extensions — unexplained gaps in filing history raise questions.
      </p>

      <h3>2. Profit and Loss Statements — 3 Years, Monthly</h3>
      <p>
        Monthly P&amp;Ls allow buyers to identify seasonality, revenue trends, and anomalous months.
        Annual P&amp;Ls hide too much. The monthly statements should come from your accounting software
        (QuickBooks, Xero, Wave) — hand-prepared spreadsheet P&amp;Ls invite skepticism. They should
        be consistent with your tax returns — major discrepancies require explanation.
      </p>

      <h3>3. Current Year Interim P&amp;L</h3>
      <p>
        A year-to-date P&amp;L as of the most recent month. This shows buyers how the current year
        is tracking relative to prior years and allows them to calculate a trailing-twelve-month SDE.
        If the current year is significantly below prior years, prepare a written explanation.
      </p>

      <h3>4. Balance Sheet</h3>
      <p>
        A current balance sheet as of the most recent month-end. Key items buyers examine:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Accounts receivable aging — are receivables collectible, or are there significant overdue amounts?</li>
        <li>Inventory — how current is it, and is it at cost or market value?</li>
        <li>Equipment and fixed assets — depreciated book value vs. actual market value</li>
        <li>Accounts payable — are there significant vendor balances that will transfer?</li>
        <li>Debt — what liabilities will be paid off at closing vs. assumed by the buyer?</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>5. SDE Recast / Add-Back Schedule</h3>
      <p>
        This is the most important document you will prepare. The recast P&amp;L reconstructs your
        income statement to show true owner earnings, with every add-back explicitly identified and
        its documentation referenced. Format:
      </p>
      <div class="data-table-wrap">
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th scope="col">Item</th>
              <th scope="col">Amount</th>
              <th scope="col">Documentation</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Net profit per tax return</td><td>$XX,XXX</td><td>Form 1120-S, Line X</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Owner salary W-2</td><td>+$XX,XXX</td><td>W-2, Payroll records</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Owner health insurance</td><td>+$XX,XXX</td><td>Insurance premium statements</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Owner vehicle</td><td>+$XX,XXX</td><td>Mileage log, vehicle registration</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Depreciation</td><td>+$XX,XXX</td><td>Schedule of depreciation, tax return</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Interest expense</td><td>+$XX,XXX</td><td>Loan statements</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Non-recurring: [description]</td><td>+$XX,XXX</td><td>Invoice or explanation</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Total SDE</strong></td><td><strong>$XXX,XXX</strong></td><td></td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h3>6. Bank Statements — 12–24 Months</h3>
      <p>
        Buyers verify that revenue deposits match the reported P&amp;L. If your P&amp;L shows $800,000
        in revenue but your bank deposits total $650,000, you will be asked to explain the difference.
        Cash transactions not deposited cannot be credibly added back. Organize statements by account
        and year — buyers should be able to verify any P&amp;L line without hunting through unsorted records.
      </p>

      <h3>7. Equipment and Asset List</h3>
      <p>
        A detailed list of all equipment, vehicles, and fixtures included in the sale, with:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Description and model/year</li>
        <li>Age and current condition</li>
        <li>Estimated fair market value</li>
        <li>Leased vs. owned (with lease terms for leased equipment)</li>
        <li>Any known deferred maintenance or required repairs</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Buyers will physically inspect this list during diligence. Overstating asset values or
        omitting known maintenance needs will surface and damage trust at a critical point.
      </p>

      <h3>8. Customer and Contract Summary</h3>
      <p>
        Without naming specific customers (confidentiality is maintained until late diligence),
        provide a summary showing:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Revenue by customer tier (e.g., top 10 customers as % of revenue, without names)</li>
        <li>Active contracts with terms and renewal dates</li>
        <li>Customer retention rate year-over-year</li>
        <li>Average transaction value and frequency</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>9. Lease Copies and Key Contracts</h3>
      <p>
        Copies of all facility leases (with amendments), equipment leases, franchise agreements,
        supplier contracts, and any other agreements material to the business. Buyers' attorneys
        review these to assess assignment risk, renewal options, and change-of-control provisions.
      </p>

      <h3>10. Employee Summary</h3>
      <p>
        A list of all employees (positions, not names for confidentiality) with:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Role and tenure</li>
        <li>Full-time vs. part-time status</li>
        <li>Compensation (salary or hourly rate)</li>
        <li>Any non-compete or non-solicitation agreements</li>
        <li>Key roles the owner holds that would need replacement</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>The Virtual Data Room</h2>
      <p>
        Organize all documents in a virtual data room — a shared cloud folder (Google Drive, Dropbox,
        or a dedicated VDR platform) structured so a buyer can navigate without guidance. Folder structure:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>01 Tax Returns / [Year 1, Year 2, Year 3]</li>
        <li>02 P&amp;Ls / [Annual, Monthly by Year, Current YTD]</li>
        <li>03 Balance Sheets</li>
        <li>04 Bank Statements</li>
        <li>05 SDE Recast and Add-Back Schedule</li>
        <li>06 Assets and Equipment</li>
        <li>07 Leases and Contracts</li>
        <li>08 Employees</li>
        <li>09 Customers and Revenue Summary</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        A buyer who receives a well-organized data room makes faster decisions and is less likely
        to use diligence confusion as a negotiating tool. Disorganized records signal disorganized
        management and invite lower offers.
      </p>

